        <briefdescription>
<para><bold> Returns the the weight needed for polynomial interpolation. </bold> </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para><simplesect kind="par"><title>Purpose</title><para></para>
</simplesect>
The <formula id="124">$k$</formula>-th order approximation polynomial <formula id="126">$P(x)$</formula> through function values <formula id="127">$\{(x_l,f(x_l),l=0,\dots,k)\}$</formula> with <formula id="128">$x_{l+1}-x_{l}=h$</formula> is given by</para>
<para><formula id="129">\begin{align*}  P(x) = \sum^k_{\alpha=0}\sum^k_{l=0} c_{\alpha,l}\, \left(\frac{x}{h}\right)^\alpha  f(x_l)
\end{align*}</formula></para>
<para><computeroutput><ref refid="classintegration_1_1Integrator_a306e7e8d1bf3992f5c9a038420239bd6_1a306e7e8d1bf3992f5c9a038420239bd6" kindref="member">poly_interpolation</ref></computeroutput> returns the coeffient <formula id="130">$c_{\alpha,l}$</formula> for given indicies <formula id="131">$\alpha,l$</formula>.</para>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>alpha</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para><blockquote><para>First index of coefficients. </para>
</blockquote></para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>l</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Second index of coefficients.  </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
